post_text:
With the growth in our enrollment numbers over the past 3 months, we've had many questions about the availability of certain courses and electives. The Academic team would like to reassure our families that we will have a number of electives for our families to choose from.

PALCS remains dedicated to providing our students with quality educational opportunities.

While we do not guarantee enrollment in any course, we continually assess the need to increase our staff, and adjust class sizes to meet the needs of our students. This has always been, and remains, a commitment of PALCS leadership.

Lastly, PALCS would like to thank our former and current families. Our reputation as a cyber school, and the growth we are experiencing is a direct result of your voice!

The PALCS admissions team is dedicated to processing enrollments as quickly and thoroughly as possible in the order complete applications with documents were received. Our team is making progress and applications submitted before 5 pm on July 27th are continuing to be processed daily.

We are focused on the start of school and we are working to get our new students the information, learning tools, and support they need. We are committed to maintaining the quality of online education we have built over the past sixteen years.

We appreciate your patience as the PALCS community grows. Thank you!

ATTENTION: At this time (Effective 5 pm on Monday 7/27), all new PALCS applications will be entered into a waiting list.

If you have already submitted an application, you will still be enrolled with PALCS for the upcoming school year! Please keep in mind: we are unable to schedule an orientation until your submitted application and critical documents are received (birth certificate, immunization records, proofs of residence.

Due to the higher volume of applications this year, please note that our admissions team is currently processing applications from July 13th. You are likely to experience a wait of several business days. We are processing applications as quickly as possible; thank you for your continued patience!

post_text: After 17 years of dedicated service, Mrs. Debby Weisbach is retiring from PALCS! Debby has been our head of our Student Services Division. Under Debby's direction, we have built an orientation team that sets the stage for a student being successful at PALCS through training, support materials, and ongoing face to face support. During her time with PALCS, she has loved watching the school grow and change to meet the needs of students and parents who‚Äôve joined PALCS family over the years. Thank you, Debby, for all that you have done during your time at PALCS, you will certainly be missed. Let's all wish her a wonderful retirement! üå∫

post_text: After over 15 years with PALCS, Ms. Valerie Harris, PALCS Supervisor of Induction & Mentoring is retiring! Val has been with PALCS since 2005 and has served as an Elementary Teacher, Elementary Principal, and as Supervisor of Induction and Mentoring. In her last role, she had helped our new teachers to learn our system, become great teachers, and also for these same teachers to become mentors for other new teachers joining the team. Thank you, Val, for all that you have done during your time at PALCS, you will certainly be missed. Let's all wish her a happy and fulfilling retirement! üå∫

*** UPDATE: The student internet filter should now be working normally. If there are still any problems or questions please have students fill out a ticket at support.palcs.org or give the Helpdesk a call at x1616. ***

We are currently experiencing problems with our student internet filter. Any students working from their school computers will see error messages when trying to load websites. They may intermittently be able to load some pages after a restart, but until we get the filter working again they will continue to have problems. They can still access the school website and their work from personal devices without any problems. We are working on the problem now and will send out updates as soon as we have more information.

Sorry for the inconvenience,

PALCS IT Department

post_text:
Congratulations to PALCS and CPFA junior, Benjamin Amidon, who has qualified to become a part of the Pennsylvania Music Educators Association All-State Orchestra this spring!

Ben placed first chair on Violin 2 in an audition process that had to take place online due to the Region Orchestra Festival being canceled. Ben lives in Bethlehem, PA, and auditioned for PMEA honors ensembles with Mr. West as his sponsor. "Ben had the highest score at pre-auds, which included over 60 violinists from public schools in Philadelphia, Delaware, and Chester Counties, and placed second overall at Region Orchestra, which includes students from those counties plus Montgomery and Bucks Counties," Mr. West explains of Benjamin's accomplishments!

Keep up the great work, Ben - we are all so proud of you!

#PALCSProud

PALCS high school student, Carinne, pursues her dream of horseback riding while also working and training several hours a week.

When asked what advice she had for other students who may be juggling a full schedule, Carinne commented, ‚ÄúYou have to push yourself to get on top of things or else it‚Äôs going to hurt you in the long run.‚Äù Carrine explains that her Junior year was extremely challenging academically. "I didn‚Äôt admit to the fact that I wasn‚Äôt trying to get my homework done and kept trying to blame work. It seems easier not to do the assignments but when your grades are bad, colleges won‚Äôt feel sympathy for you.‚Äù She desires for students to think about their future, and how beneficial it will be to be organized and motivated.

PA Leadership Charter School‚Äôs Mock Trial teams are set to compete in the Chester County District Finals this evening, February 25th.

The University Scholars Program at PALCS offered an A team and B team for this level of competition. Both teams advanced beyond the initial round on February 10th and 11th, and pushed through a fierce semi-final round on the 24th.

The winning team of this PALCS-USP A v. PALCS-USP B match will move on to the regional level of competition. This is the first time that any school, much less a cyber charter school, has had multiple teams vying for the honor of the district title.

The success of both teams is truly a testament to the value and positive impact of a PALCS education. The final round will begin at 4:30 pm at the Chester County Justice Center.

Good luck to both teams!

PALCS Middle School students met up at our Western office for a double feature presentation from the Carnegie Museum of Natural History's "Bring the Museum to You" program. During this Middle School Lab, the museum brought two presentations: Dino Detectives & Nighttime Animals!

With Dino Detectives, students examined the diversity & adaptations of dinosaurs across time by comparing dinosaur teeth, claws, & other replica fossils. In Nighttime Animals, students designed their own constellations, identified the sounds of nocturnal animals, learned about how nocturnal predators hunt their prey, & met some live animal ambassadors from the museum. Check out our recap video of this fun event!

http://bit.ly/2S2dU7d

Strengthening Families Program: For Parents and Youth 10-14 is a nationally recognized program, designed to offer family-focused interventions with the intent of reducing the likelihood for substance abuse or other problems associated with the teen years. This FREE 7 week program is open to anyone in the community that wishes to participate! Each week will consist of a free group dinner, separate group activities & discussions for parents & youth, then a joint activity at the end of the night where parents & youth come back together to foster family bonding.

The first night of this program starts tomorrow for anyone local to Oxford, PA.

Today wraps up National School Counseling Week for 2020! Though today may be the last day of this week-long celebration, showing love & appreciation for our PALCS Guidance Department never has to end!!üíõ

Rachel, a current PALCS Parent, recently shared with us her positive experience with our Guidance Department: "When my son arrived at PALCS, Ms. Patty & Ms. Dawson were very helpful in getting him registered. He started two weeks late, but Ms. Dawson made herself available to our family to ensure that he caught up with the other students. She also assisted with being a "voice" for him when it came to communicating with his teachers. She always made sure that she found a solution for us -- whether it was concerns about a class or issues with the laptop/printer. When we were registering for Spring classes, I realized that my son had two classes overlapping, and Ms. Patty worked with Ms. Dawson to get him switched right away. The process of registering for classes and receiving support has been awesome!"

What positive stories do you have about our Guidance Department? Share them below!

post_text:
Because of #schoolchoice, 8 year old Joshua Aguirre has been able to pursue his dreams. Joshua is passionate about Taekwondo -- he is a USA Taekwondo National medalist, & has already received a total of 93 medals (85 of them being gold), as well as over 20 1st place finishes in competitions throughout PA, NJ, NY, MD, & NC. Joshua has also traveled to Costa Rica & Toronto. His mother tells us that he is one of the youngest student-athletes to ever earn a Black Belt in PA, as well as one of the youngest Latinos in the US to earn a Black Belt.

Joshua will be competing in Mexico Feb. 6-9 in a Taekwondo championship -- congratulations on all your successes, Joshua! Wish Joshua luck in the comments!!üíô If you wish to support Joshua & his dreams, click the link below: http://bit.ly/2S58S8H

Strengthening Families Program: For Parents and Youth 10-14 is a nationally recognized program, designed to offer family-focused interventions with the intent of reducing the likelihood for substance abuse or other problems associated with the teen years. This FREE 7 week program is open to anyone in the community that wishes to participate! Each week will consist of a free group dinner, separate group activities & discussions for parents & youth, then a joint activity at the end of the night where parents & youth come back together to foster family bonding.

The first night of this program starts tomorrow for anyone local to Coatesville, PA.

THIS Monday kicks off #PALCSspirit week!! Since 2011, PALCS & other K-12 options (such as traditional public schools, public charter schools, public magnet schools, private schools, online academies, and homeschooling) have partnered with National School Choice Week to "shine a spotlight on effective education options for children."

As a way to raise awareness, PALCS will be posting information blogs about how cyber school is an effective choice for children, as well as participating in fun Spirit Week activities!

HERE'S WHAT TO DO: take a picture of yourself participating in one or all 5 Spirit Week activities listed in the image below & tag us at Pennsylvania Leadership Charter School (PALCS) or with the hashtag #PALCSspirit! Give a short caption on why YOU chose PALCS! All participants will be entered in our random drawing to win a School Choice Week scarf & Be MARVELous with PALCS magnet. Who's ready for Monday??

For the past several years, PALCS 4th & 5th grade teachers & students participate in a day of service at the Cradles to Crayons facility in Philadelphia! Students & teachers work a shift in The Giving Factory Warehouse, where they participate in hands-on processing of the donated goods that flow in on a regular basis.

Our Elementary students will be serving at Cradles to Crayons again on February 14th! Interested in signing up? Last day to sign up is on Friday, February 7th... registration can be found on PALCSchool.

http://bit.ly/2TNTNuK

Meet Haozhou Wang, a musically inclined high school student at here PALCS! Since an early age, Haozhou developed a deep love of music, learning to play the piano around age 3. Now, Haozhou is an accomplished award-winner in several international piano competitions. On top of that, he takes courses at The Julliard School in New York.

We are extremely proud of Haozhou for all of his accomplishments and successes! Check out Haozhou's spotlight video on our Youtube channel:

Happy Candy Cane day! Only a few days left in the holiday season to enjoy these festive treats, so get 'em while you can!!

Did you know that...
- candy canes have been around since the 17th century
- candy canes didn't always have their famous stripes! The red stripes didn't start appearing consistently until the 1900s
- the largest candy cane was featured in the Guinness Book of World Records, which was 51 feet long!

Three one-of-a-kind capitals. Three remarkable countries. Our tour of Scandinavia begins in Oslo, home of Viking kings and canyon-cut fjords. Next it‚Äôs Copenhagen, Hans Christian Andersen‚Äôs fairy tale city. Here you‚Äôll climb the 17th-century Round Tower, Europe‚Äôs oldest functioning observatory. We will end our exploration in Stockholm, where we will see the Royal Palace and the city‚Äôs oldest church, dating from 1306. There is also the opportunity to expand the tour to include Finland. We will talk more about the itinerary at our meeting.
Please join Mrs. Intelicato on Wednesday, December 11th and Thursday, December 12th at 6:30 in her zoom room. Please see the Lobby Page for the zoom link.

Website: http://bit.ly/38s0RC1

Today is Special Education Dayüíõ Here at PALCS we have a wonderful Special Education program dedicated to our students‚Äô success. This year around 30% of our student population was enrolled as Special Education. Every Special Education student is assigned a Resource Teacher that acts as their case manager and is there to work with the General Education teachers in relation to getting the students everything they need in order to succeed. We are incredibly grateful for the AMAZING staff of teachers & administrators who help serve our families!

For more information on our Special Education Department, visit our site at http://bit.ly/33kogl7
